steps.description:
Hold the cabbage still with one hand. Pick up a large, sharp knife in your other hand and cut the cabbage in half through the stem end. If desired, cut the cabbage further into quarters by cutting each half in half again lengthwise. Cabbage will take longer to cook if left in halves, but otherwise, it is just as easy to prepare as quartered cabbage. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d7/Steam-Cabbage-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/d/d7/Steam-Cabbage-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/aid3221944-v4-728px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"485","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If you see any signs of insects or worms inside the cabbage, you do not need to toss the whole thing out. Instead, soak the head of cabbage in heavily salted water for 20 minutes. Cut away the damaged portions and prepare as normal. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/bb/Steam-Cabbage-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/b/bb/Steam-Cabbage-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/aid3221944-v4-728px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"485","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Cut wedge-shaped sections from the bottom of each half or quarter to remove the rough stem pieces. The stems will need to be cut out at an angle. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/7a/Steam-Cabbage-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/7/7a/Steam-Cabbage-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/aid3221944-v4-728px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"485","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Note that for cabbage with long, loose leaves, such as napa cabbage and bok choy, the leaves should be left intact and on the stem. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/0d/Steam-Cabbage-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/0/0d/Steam-Cabbage-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/aid3221944-v4-728px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"485","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If you want to shred the cabbage before steaming it, slice each quarter into thin pieces and separate the layers by hand. Alternatively, you could shred the cabbage by sliding quartered heads across a sharp mandoline. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/82/Steam-Cabbage-Step-5Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-5Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/8/82/Steam-Cabbage-Step-5Bullet1.jpg/aid3221944-v4-728px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-5Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"485","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If shredding napa cabbage or bok choy, slice the cabbage crosswise rather than lengthwise and separate the layers. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/ad/Steam-Cabbage-Step-5Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-5Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/a/ad/Steam-Cabbage-Step-5Bullet2.jpg/aid3221944-v4-728px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-5Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"485","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Meanwhile, fit a steamer basket into the stockpot, noting that the bottom of the basket should not come into contact with the water. The stockpot should only be about 1/4 full with water, if not less. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/4\/45\/Steam-Cabbage-Step-7Bullet1.jpg\/v4-459px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-7Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"\/images\/thumb\/4\/45\/Steam-Cabbage-Step-7Bullet1.jpg\/aid3221944-v4-728px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-7Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"485","licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

After placing the stockpot on your stove, heat it over high heat to get a rapid boil going. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/5\/54\/Steam-Cabbage-Step-7Bullet2.jpg\/v4-459px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-7Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"\/images\/thumb\/5\/54\/Steam-Cabbage-Step-7Bullet2.jpg\/aid3221944-v4-728px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-7Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"485","licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

You could add salt to the water, if desired, which will add subtle flavor to the cabbage as it cooks. Do not do this if you plan on salting the cabbage directly, though. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/6\/61\/Steam-Cabbage-Step-7Bullet3.jpg\/v4-459px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-7Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"\/images\/thumb\/6\/61\/Steam-Cabbage-Step-7Bullet3.jpg\/aid3221944-v4-728px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-7Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"485","licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

The bottom of the steamer basket should never come into direct contact with the boiling water. If the boiling water reaches through the bottom of the basket, you may end up boiling the bottom part of the cabbage instead of steaming it. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/0\/0d\/Steam-Cabbage-Step-7Bullet4.jpg\/v4-459px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-7Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"\/images\/thumb\/0\/0d\/Steam-Cabbage-Step-7Bullet4.jpg\/aid3221944-v4-728px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-7Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"485","licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

If you do not have a steamer basket, you could use a metal or wire mesh colander, instead. Just make sure that the colander can rest on the lip of the stockpot without falling in and without preventing the lid from fitting over it.

Spread the cabbage out in an even layer. If steaming shredded cabbage, you will need to make sure that the cabbage is evenly distributed throughout the bottom of the steamer basket. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b7/Steam-Cabbage-Step-8Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-8Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/b/b7/Steam-Cabbage-Step-8Bullet1.jpg/aid3221944-v4-728px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-8Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"485","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If steaming quarters or halves, arrange the pieces so that they are touching and facing stem-side down. Each piece should be equally exposed to the bottom of the basket. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/30/Steam-Cabbage-Step-8Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-8Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/3/30/Steam-Cabbage-Step-8Bullet2.jpg/aid3221944-v4-728px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-8Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"485","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

The exact amount of time the cabbage needs to be steamed for will vary on the type and on how fine the cabbage was cut before you placed it in the basket. To promote even cooking, you may flip the wedges or halves over halfway through the cooking time. Other than that, however, you should not lift the lid of the pot. Doing so will release the steam needed to cook the cabbage. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f7/Steam-Cabbage-Step-10Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-10Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/f/f7/Steam-Cabbage-Step-10Bullet1.jpg/aid3221944-v4-728px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-10Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"485","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

In general, cook shredded cabbage for 5 to 8 minutes. Napa cabbage, savoy cabbage, and bok choy, however, may cook in only 3 to 5 minutes. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f3/Steam-Cabbage-Step-10Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-10Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/f/f3/Steam-Cabbage-Step-10Bullet2.jpg/aid3221944-v4-728px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-10Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"485","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

In general, quarters should be cooked for 10 to 12 minutes. Tall cabbages like napa cabbage and bok choy tend to finish on the shorter end. Savoy cabbage can cook in as few as 5 minutes and as many as 10 minutes. Red cabbage may take a few minutes longer than other varieties. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/22/Steam-Cabbage-Step-10Bullet3.jpg/v4-459px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-10Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/2/22/Steam-Cabbage-Step-10Bullet3.jpg/aid3221944-v4-728px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-10Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"485","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Add an additional 1 or 2 minutes onto the quartered cooking time when you are steaming cabbage halves. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/26/Steam-Cabbage-Step-10Bullet4.jpg/v4-459px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-10Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/2/26/Steam-Cabbage-Step-10Bullet4.jpg/aid3221944-v4-728px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-10Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"485","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Remove the steamer basket from the stockpot and let it drain on clean paper towels for a few minutes before serving. If desired, you could sprinkle the cabbage with additional salt and pepper or drizzle melted butter or olive oil over it. Toss well yet gently to coat. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/6b/Steam-Cabbage-Step-11Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-11Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/6/6b/Steam-Cabbage-Step-11Bullet1.jpg/aid3221944-v4-728px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-11Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"485","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

For a stronger flavor, drizzle 2 to 3 Tbsp (30 to 45 ml) of apple cider vinegar over the cabbage and toss to coat. This works especially well with napa cabbage and red cabbage. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/46/Steam-Cabbage-Step-11Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-11Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/4/46/Steam-Cabbage-Step-11Bullet2.jpg/aid3221944-v4-728px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-11Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"485","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Arrange the cabbage so that it is in even layers inside the dish. If steaming shredded cabbage, make sure that the cabbage is evenly distributed throughout the bottom of the dish. It does not need to be in a single flat layer, but the layers of cabbage should be even to promote even cooking. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/08/Steam-Cabbage-Step-12Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-12Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/0/08/Steam-Cabbage-Step-12Bullet1.jpg/aid3221944-v4-728px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-12Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"485","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Note that shredded cabbage is not recommended for microwave steaming since the bottom layer will ultimately be boiled instead of steamed. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/7e/Steam-Cabbage-Step-12Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-12Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/7/7e/Steam-Cabbage-Step-12Bullet2.jpg/aid3221944-v4-728px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-12Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"485","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If steaming quarters or halves, arrange the pieces so that they are touching and facing stem-side down. Do not stack or layer the wedges. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e7/Steam-Cabbage-Step-12Bullet3.jpg/v4-459px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-12Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/e/e7/Steam-Cabbage-Step-12Bullet3.jpg/aid3221944-v4-728px-Steam-Cabbage-Step-12Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"485","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}
